sentence-detokenized: Cricket - Leicestershire top the table with an innings win.
West Indies all-rounder Phil Simmons made 4 for 38 on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by 39 runs an innings in two days to go top of the County Championship table.
However, the top spot may not last long as rival teams such as Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey are close to victory and Kent have fallen behind in their rain-affected game against Nottinghamshire.
After dismissing Somerset for 83 on the first morning at Grace Road, Leicestershire finished the first innings on 94 runs and were bowled out for 296, with Andy Caddick taking 83 for three.
Somerset, 213 runs down, got off to a solid start in their second innings, but Simmons was bundled out for 174.
However, Essex look certain to regain top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such won the Yorkshire game at Headingley.
Hussain was considered a must for England's one-day team and his first Championship century of the season - 158 - helped Essex reach 372 and take an 82 lead into the first innings.
However, off-spinner Thatch took 4 for 24 in 48 balls to leave the visitors on 119 for 5 and pray for rain.
At the Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis continued to silence his critics with 80 not out against Warwickshire on Friday following his 4 for 45 on Thursday.
He finished on 429 for Surrey, with England hopeful Mark Butcher scoring 70 and Surrey leading by 234 runs.
Derbyshire made 133-5 in Worcestershire's second innings and were looking for their first win since 1936, but just 100 more runs were needed to avoid defeat in the innings.
Australian Tom Moody scored 82 for six, while Chris Adams and Tim O'Gorman scored 123 and 109 respectively, as Derbyshire led by 471 runs and 233 runs in the first innings.
After a frustrating first day at the mercy of the weather, Kent stepped up a gear and dismissed Nottinghamshire in 214.
However, former England fast bowler Martin McCaig scored 55 for four and was restricted to 84 by Paul Johnson.
At the time of the stamp Kent was 108-3.

Alan Shearer, the world's costliest footballer, was named England's new captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for £15 million (£23.4 million), takes over from Tony Adams, who led the team to the European Championships in June, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Pratt are both injured and will miss England's opening World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer will captain on trial, but new manager Glenn Hoddle said there was no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton skipper could not make the post his own.
'I am convinced that Alan is the right man for the job,' Hoddle said.
'But when I spoke to Alan, he wanted it.
"It is very difficult to come to a 100 per cent conclusion on something like this in four days...
But he knows how to conduct himself, his teammates respect him and he knows what's going on with the team, even when he's playing up front."
Shearer's Euro 96 strike partner Teddy Sheringham was injured on Friday and withdrew from the squad.
He is likely to be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle team-mate Les Ferdinand.

Football - Rotor fans shut out after violence in Volgograd.

Rotor Volgograd's short-lived league championship ended when fans threw bottles and stones at Dinamo Moscow players during a 1-0 home defeat, forcing the next home game to be played behind closed doors.
The head of the Russian League's Disciplinary Committee, Anatoly Gorokhovsky, announced on Friday that Rotor will play Lada Togliatti on 3 September in an empty stand.
The club was fined $1,000 for eliminating Manchester United in last year's UEFA Cup.
Despite the defeat, Lothar is still in a good position with 11 Championship games to go.
Three points behind Alanya and two points behind Dinamo Moscow, Volgograd has a one-game lead at the top and a two-game lead over the Moscow club.
Boxing - Panama's Roberto Duran fights against the sands of time.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran steps into the ring on Saturday in yet another ageless attempt to keep his long career alive.
In a super middleweight non-title fight in Panama City, 45-year-old Duran will face little-known Mexican Ariel Cruz (30).
The match, Duran's first in his home country in a decade, is billed here as 'the return of a legend', and Duran still talks about it in a way that reminds us of his heyday.
This match is to prepare my mind.
Durand told Reuters that he will not retire.
However, officials acknowledge that the man who has been champion in four weight classes - lightweight, welterweight, junior middleweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"Every time he fights, he is on the final frontier of his career.
Ramon Manzanares, president of the Panama Boxing Association, said: 'If he loses on Saturday, his status as one of the world's great boxers could go down.
Duran has a 97-12 record spanning 30 years and can win a 10-round bout to earn a rematch with Puerto Rico's Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho faced the Panamanian in a controversial title match in Atlantic City in June, which he won on points.

Tennis - Tarango, O'Brien produce twin comebacks at lights-down.
Andre Agassi escaped disaster on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalists Marivai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky on a tumultuous night at the US Open.

Eleventh seed Washington was unable to replicate his miraculous Wimbledon upset, losing to red-hot wildcard Alex O'Brien 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 on the stadium court after two hours and 51 minutes of hard-fought action.
In the grandstand next door, 10th seed Rios lost to Wimbledon-linked player and bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The feisty left-hander defeated the Chilean player 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's programme was going well, but the former champion Agassi, seeded sixth, had to come from behind to win 18 of his last 19 games against India's Leander Paes, 3-6 0-4.
However, the night belonged to the up-and-comers.
Washington recovered from two sets down 1-5 in the third set against Todd Martin in the Wimbledon semi-finals, and it looked like he would stage another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, who won in New Haven two weeks ago for his first professional title, was 5-4 serving for the match in the third set, but Washington fought back hard.
O'Brien, 26, kept telling himself that he had to keep giving himself the best chance to win, keep fighting and something might happen.
'Normally I would have folded my tent and left, but this time I kept my cool.
O'Brien, a former National Collegiate Champion, dominated Washington with 17 aces and never gave up until the end.
In the fifth set, serve continued until the sixth game, when Washington shrugged off a break point with a forehand winner and then netted a backhand to give O'Brien a 4-2 lead.
Then, from 40-0, Washington netted a backhand to win her eighth match point and hold at 5-2.
'You just keep fighting and trying to get him to play a little bit.
I think he got a little tight at some moments, " said Washington.
However, I think they provided a pretty good service when we needed it."

Two years ago at Wimbledon, Tarango, who was fined $28,000 and suspended from this tournament by the All England Club, tangoed with Rios in the grandstand for two hours and 24 minutes, provoking calls and fans to be very active.
Cheering crowds cheered on the distracted Chileans and booed the big Americans, drawing attention to them.
Tarango, ranked 104th, said, "I'm an emotional player."
I think we were very focused tonight and played well."
The match went to a third set tie-break, which the USA won 7-5 to the delight of the crowd.
"I love the audience, even if they boo me every day.
It inspires me to play my best tennis," said Tarango.
'I played some of my best tennis when I was at university when a frat threw beer at me.
If that was the case every day, I think everyone would enjoy tennis a lot more."
Rios was not happy with Tarango's antics.
I think we played really badly.
It was difficult to play at night.
We lost too many points that we will never lose.
"You don't see the ball as you see it during the day.
I play an American, so that's why I play at night.
I didn't feel good on the court."
After the match, Tarango gave the crowd a sarcastic kiss and gave the Rios supporters a full onlooker's salute as he shook his body.
Tarango said of the fans, "I support their enthusiasm."
At the same time, they are overtly supportive towards me.
I thought I could give them a bit of a raspberry after we won."
NFL American Football, Randall Cunningham retires.
Randall Cunningham, the all-time leading rusher as a quarterback in the National Football League and one of the most athletic players ever to line up under centre, retired on Thursday.
Cunningham spent his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
A three-time Pro Bowl selection, Cunningham ran for 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
Cunningham said, "I want to thank the Eagles organisation and the wonderful fans in Philadelphia for supporting me throughout my career."
"I am sad to be leaving, but I am looking forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other hobbies that I have been putting off for a while."
Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie said, "Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history."
Randle was a cornerstone of the Eagles during his 11 years in Philadelphia, bringing many great moments not only to Philadelphia fans, but to the NFL as a whole."
A second-round pick in 1985, Cunningham completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7%) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already signed up as a broadcaster.
